Ah, now I get your exact question, mate â€” this is a subtle but important point. Letâ€™s break it down clearly.

1ï¸âƒ£ Server Component â†’ Client Component

You can render a Client Component inside a Server Component, yes.

The Server Component can fetch data and pass it as a prop (even as a promise) to the Client Component.

Example:

// Server Component
export default async function Page() {
  const posts = getPosts(); // returns a promise
  return <Posts posts={posts} />; // Posts is a Client Component
}


Here, the Client Component doesnâ€™t fetch anything itself, it just reads the promise using use (or handles interactivity).

âœ… This works perfectly if the Server already has the data.

2ï¸âƒ£ Why useEffect is still needed

useEffect is needed only in these situations:

Client-only data fetching

When data is not available on the server (e.g., browser API, user-specific data, local storage).

Example: fetching user-specific info after login.

Dynamic or interactive requests

Like filters, searches, infinite scroll, button clicks.

Server Components canâ€™t handle client-triggered events, only pre-rendered data.

External APIs from the browser

If you need to fetch something directly from the client (for example, a public API that requires client headers or tokens), Server Components canâ€™t do this.

3ï¸âƒ£ TL;DR

Server â†’ Client Component: Great for static or pre-fetched data; no useEffect needed.

useEffect: Needed when data depends on client-side context or user interaction.

ğŸ’¡ Simple rule:

If your data comes from the server and can be passed as props â†’ use use hook or just pass the promise.
If your data depends on the client or changes due to user actions â†’ use useEffect.